In [[Stagecraft|technical theater]], '''spot rigging''' is the practice of using a [[fly system]] to fly something specific for a show which does not use the venue's standard rigging. For example, flying [[Theatrical scenery|scenery]] on an ordinary [[batten]] would not qualify as spot rigging; flying a chandelier on a dedicated line would be. Likewise, if a wall were being flown in on a batten which was installed at an angle neither parallel nor perpendicular to the [[proscenium]] line, it would qualify as spot rigging, because custom setting of lift lines would be required.


